Background¶

Neutrino detection: importance and methods

Related experiment: DUNE, neutrino oscillations, LAr chamber

Pixel detector technology to overcome challenges in detecting particle in large scale (kilotons) detector Previous version: Analog Q-pix, 16-channel bullseye, Argon gas chamber --> prototype for electronics test

This version: ASIC circuits, LAr, smaller scale of more realistic usage

  • Impurities in Ar like Oxygen, Water leaking in from outside the chamber can make lifetime measurement inaccurate. When we did with analog Q-pix, we used PyBoltz to calculate the affect the impurities at different concentration has to the electron diffusion (the distribution of electrons cloud corelates to how much impurities are attached to the drifting electrons).

  • For most efficient test, we want Liquid Argon to be pure all the time. Thus, we construct a purifier which filters out Oxygen and Water during regeneration process and provides us with pure liquid argon to refill the TPC.

  • This experiment involves constructing the purity monitor (field cage) and a purifier (nipple with copper catalysts and molecular sieves) to experiment with the process. The main goal this summer is to get the system working and measure the purity of the output determined by electron lifetime measurement.

  • Once the Q-Pix ASICs arrive, we can install it into the chamber with liquid argon and collect data.

Purity Monitor¶

Impurities in liquid Argon can ionize and lead to electrical discharge between the cathode and anode. The measurement of these discharges indicates the impurity level.

The purity monitor consists of a field cage generating uniform electric field. Electrons are generated at the cathode of the field cage via the photoelectric effect. A series of ultraviolet light pulses from xenon flash lamp is transmitted through a fiber optic cable to the photo-cathode positioned at the center of the field cage, stripping electrons from the material (we use a gold-coated plate). These electrons then drift upward through liquid Argon from cathode and are collected at anode. Wire meshes are placed on both ends of field cage to shield the cathode and anode from induced current.

Pressure Gauges:¶

We use rough and turbo pumps to put the system into vacuum and use pressure gauges to monitor the pressure drop as time preceeds. We use Convectron Gauge (CG) and Ion Gauge (IG).

CG works under high pressure down to 5e-2 Torr and IG only works from pressure less than 5e-2 Torr. As the pump the system down, we switch from CG to IG for an accurate low pressure readings.

IG can be damaged under high pressure, it is crucial to have the system switch the IG off when the pressure exceeds its 5e-2 Torr limit.

There are 2 ways to do this: 1) Device's built-in logic: Connect pin1,2 (GND) of the pressure gauge together, IG will be auto-on-off based on CG pressure. Switch to display summary to show both CG, IG. This way is safer as we have display and independent of the PC status.

2) Python control through serial communcation: The Hornet (pressure gauges) connection to RS485, TXD A+ (red pin9 (B+)), TXD B- (purple pin6 (A-)). Use the code Here to send command and read result in ASCII. Use the value to decide if IG should be on/off.

Field Cage: Uniform Drift Field Simulation (FreeFEM)¶

plot to simulate Electric field in the field cage geometry (separation) and applied voltage at each ring, ensure it's uniform.

FreeFEM code: contains Python script to generate the .edp file to solve the field from field cage geometry and applied voltage, saved result in .txt file for plotting in MatLab, and screenshots of the equipotential plot which shows our configurations provide the uniform drift field between cathode wire mesh and anode wire mesh.

def get_slope(x, y):
    coefficients = np.polyfit(x, y, 1)
    slope = coefficients[0]
    intercept = coefficients[1]
    return slope, intercept

20240612 Electron lifetime and Impurities calculation¶

Impurities in the medium attaches to the drifting electron, causing $Q_A$, the charge measured at anode to be smaller than $Q_C$ at cathode. The ratio $Q_A/Q_C$ is used to calculate electron lifetime.

Drift electron attenuation in a purity monitor as a function of electron lifetime: $\tau = -\frac{t_{\text{drift}}}{\ln(Q_A / Q_C)}$

#%matplotlib notebook
%matplotlib inline

def get_data(file_path):
    plt.rcParams['font.size'] = 16
    df = pd.read_csv(file_path,skiprows=14)
    time = np.array(df["TIME"])
    CH2 = np.array(df["CH2"])
    CH3 = np.array(df["CH3"])    
    return time,CH2,CH3

def calc(CV1,CV2,AV1,AV2,t1,t2,t3,t4):
    delt = round(t3-t1,1)
    QA = round(np.abs(AV2-AV1),1)
    QC = round(np.abs(CV2-CV1),1)
    ratio = round(QA/QC,2)
    tau = round(-delt/(np.log(ratio)),1)
    print(f"tdrift = {delt} s, QA = {QA} mV, QC = {QC} mV, QA/AC = {ratio},  = {tau} s")

def get_datafromdat(filename):
    with open(filename, 'r') as f:
        Timestamp, Hours, AIN0, AIN2, AIN4 = [],[],[],[],[]
        for line in f:
            columns = line.split()
            unixtime = columns[0]
            Timestamp.append(columns[0])
            
            Hours.append(datetime.datetime.fromtimestamp(float(unixtime)).strftime('%H:%M'))
            AIN0.append(round(float(columns[1]),2))
            AIN2.append(round(float(columns[3]),2))
            AIN4.append(round(float(columns[5]),2))
    return Timestamp, Hours, AIN0, AIN2, AIN4
    
def plot_T7data(filename, labels=False):
    filepath = "TempRead/"+filename
    plt.rcParams['font.size'] = 16
    Timestamp, Hours, AIN0, AIN2, AIN4 = get_datafromdat(filepath)
    colors = ["black","red","green"]
    
    evr = 100
    if labels:
        plt.plot(Hours[::evr],AIN0[::evr], label = "AIN0", color = colors[0])
        plt.plot(Hours[::evr],AIN2[::evr], label = "AIN2", color = colors[1])
        plt.plot(Hours[::evr],AIN4[::evr], label = "AIN4", color = colors[2])
    else:
        plt.plot(Hours[::evr],AIN0[::evr], color = colors[0])
        plt.plot(Hours[::evr],AIN2[::evr], color = colors[1])
        plt.plot(Hours[::evr],AIN4[::evr], color = colors[2])
    
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5), dpi=80)

20240613 GUI design for Temperature display¶

LabJack T7 appends temperature readings to a .dat file simultaneously as the datalogger update temperature plot. Python code is used to grab latest data logged on the file and display on top of the experimental setup diagram to show temperature at different location thermocouples are installed. The display helps monitor the flow of gas/liquid inside the purifier during regeneration process and help us assess the heat loss at each state.

import sys
import csv

import numpy as np

from PyQt5 import QtWidgets, QtCore

import matplotlib
matplotlib.use('Qt5Agg')
from matplotlib.backends.backend_qt5agg import FigureCanvasQTAgg as FigureCanvas
from matplotlib.figure import Figure
from IPython.display import clear_output

import matplotlib.image as mpimg

class MplCanvas(FigureCanvas):
    def __init__(self, parent=None, width=5, height=4, dpi=100):
        fig = Figure(figsize=(width, height), dpi=dpi)
        self.axes = fig.add_subplot(111)
        super(MplCanvas, self).__init__(fig)
        
        self.csv_file = 'Tempread/realtimedata_test2.csv'
        self.latest_entry = None 

        self.timer = QtCore.QTimer(self)
        self.timer.timeout.connect(self.update_image)
        self.timer.start(1000)  
    
    def latest_datacsv(self, csv_file):
        with open(csv_file, 'r') as file:
            data = csv.reader(file)
            for row in data:
                latest_entry = row
            return latest_entry
     
    def latest_datadat(self, dat_file):
        with open(dat_file, 'r') as file:
            lines = file.readlines()
            last_line = lines[-1].strip()
            latest_entry = last_line.split()
            return latest_entry
    
    def update_image(self):

        self.axes.cla() # Clear the canvas.
        
        #old code
        new_entry = self.latest_datacsv(self.csv_file)
        if new_entry and new_entry != self.latest_entry: 
            self.latest_entry = new_entry
            timestamp = str(new_entry[1])
            CH1 = round(float(new_entry[2]),2)
            CH2 = round(float(new_entry[3]),2)
            CH3 = round(float(new_entry[4]),2)
            CH4 = round(float(new_entry[5]),2)
            CH5 = round(float(new_entry[6]),2)
            CH6 = round(float(new_entry[7]),2)
            CH7 = round(float(new_entry[8]),2)

            #self.axes.scatter([1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7], [CH1, CH2, CH3, CH4, CH5, CH6, CH7]) #test
            
            #plot image 
            img = mpimg.imread('Tempread/Diagram.png')  
            self.axes.imshow(img)
            self.fontsize = 10
            #scatter plot on top of img 
            self.axes.text(430, 420, f"CH1: {CH1} C", fontsize=self.fontsize, color='black', fontweight='bold')
            self.axes.scatter(390, 350, color='black', edgecolors='white')

            self.axes.text(450, 780, f"CH2: {CH2} C", fontsize=self.fontsize, color='white', fontweight='bold')
            self.axes.scatter(500, 820, color='white', edgecolors='black')

            self.axes.text(470, 1170, f"CH3: {CH3} C", fontsize=self.fontsize, color='red', fontweight='bold')
            self.axes.scatter(470, 1100, color='red', edgecolors='white')

            self.axes.text(300, 1470, f"CH4: {CH4} C", fontsize=self.fontsize, color='lime', fontweight='bold')
            self.axes.scatter(300, 1400, color='lime', edgecolors='white')

            self.axes.text(1600, 730, f"CH5: {CH5} C", fontsize=self.fontsize, color='magenta', fontweight='bold')
            self.axes.scatter(1750, 660, color='magenta', edgecolors='white')

            self.axes.text(1500, 1270, f"CH6: {CH6} C", fontsize=self.fontsize, color='cyan', fontweight='bold')
            self.axes.scatter(1500, 1200, color='cyan', edgecolors='white')

            self.axes.text(1140, 1470, f"CH7: {CH7} C", fontsize=self.fontsize, color='blue', fontweight='bold')
            self.axes.scatter(1140, 1400, color='blue', edgecolors='white')
            
            
            self.axes.set_title(timestamp)
            self.axes.axis('off')
            # Trigger the canvas to update and redraw.
            self.draw()
            


class MainWindow(QtWidgets.QMainWindow):
    def __init__(self, *args, **kwargs):
        super(MainWindow, self).__init__(*args, **kwargs)
        self.canvas = MplCanvas(self, width=5, height=4, dpi=100)
        self.setCentralWidget(self.canvas)

        self.show()

import serial
import time
import datetime

ser = serial.Serial(
    port='COM6', 
    baudrate=19200,
    timeout=1
)

def send_data_hex(data_hex):
    data_bytes = bytes.fromhex(data_hex)  
    ser.write(data_bytes)  
    print(f"Sent: {data_hex}")

def read_bits():
    while True:
        if ser.in_waiting > 0:
            received_data = ser.read(5)  #read 5 bytes (40 bits)
            received_hex = received_data.hex()  ##to hex
            print(f"Received: {received_hex}")
            
            received_int &= 0x1FFFFFFFFF
            
            bit_17 = (received_int >> 17) & 1
            bit_18 = (received_int >> 18) & 1
            
            combined_string = f"{bit_18:02d}{bit_17:02d}"
            decimal_value = int(combined_string, 16)/10
            print(received_hex)
            print("CH1: ", decimal_value)
